      <text xml:space="preserve">{{Other uses}}
{{Original research|date=July 2008}}

A true '''duopoly''' (from [[Greek language|Greek]] ''dyo / δυο'' (two) + ''polein / πωλειν'' (to sell)) is a specific type of [[oligopoly]] where only two producers exist in one [[market]]. In reality, this definition is generally used where only two firms have dominant control over a [[market]]. In the field of [[industrial organization]], it is the most commonly studied form of oligopoly due to its simplicity.

==Duopoly models in economics==
There are two principal duopoly models, [[Cournot duopoly]] and [[Bertrand duopoly]]:

*The [[Cournot]] model, which shows that two firms assume each others output and treat this as a fixed amount, and produce in their own firm according to this.

*The [[Joseph Louis François Bertrand|Bertrand]] model, in which, in a game of two firms, each one of them will assume that the other will not change prices in response to its price cuts. When both firms use this logic, they will reach a [[Nash Equilibrium]].

==Politics==
Modern [[Politics of the United States|American politics]] has been described as a duopoly since the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] and [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] parties have dominated and framed [[policy]] debate as well as the public discourse on matters of national concern for about a century and a half. [[Third Parties]] have encountered various blocks in getting onto ballots at different levels of government as well as other electoral obstacles, more so in recent decades.

''See [[List of political parties in the United States]] for a more comprehensive look at the politics of the [[Two-party system]],  [[Duverger's law]].''

==Examples in business==
The most commonly cited duopoly is that between [[Visa Inc.|Visa]] and [[Mastercard]], who between them control a large proportion of the electronic payment processing market. In 2000 they were the defendants in a [[United States Department of Justice|US Department of Justice]] [[Sherman Antitrust Act|antitrust]] lawsuit.&lt;ref&gt;http://www.usdoj.gov/atr/cases/f1900/1973.htm&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;http://mit.edu/thistle/www/v12/2/credit.html&lt;/ref&gt; An appeal was upheld in 2004.&lt;ref&gt;http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/4014599.stm&lt;/ref&gt;

Examples where two companies control a large proportion of a market are:
{{Unreferenced section|date=March 2009}}
*[[Moody's]] and [[S&amp;P]] in the [[Credit rating|Ratings]] market
*[[Pepsi]] and [[Coca-Cola]] in the [[soft drink]] market
*[[Gillette (brand)|Gillette]] and [[Wilkinson Sword]]/[[Schick (razors)|Schick]] in the [[razor blade]] market
*[[Airbus]] and [[Boeing]] in the commercial large [[jet aircraft]] market
*[[Marvel Comics]] and [[DC Comics]] in the [[comic book]]s market
*[[Intel]] and [[AMD]] in the consumer [[desktop computer]] [[microprocessor]] market
*[[Cable modem|The local cable company]] and [[Digital Subscriber Line|the local telephone company]] in residential [[broadband Internet access]]
*[[Advanced Mobile Phone System|Analogue mobile phone service]] (1983–2008) assigned bandwidth for just two carriers (A/B); in much of North America these effectively were &quot;Alternate&quot; and &quot;[[Bell Telephone|Bell]]&quot; (or the incumbent regional telephone landline monopoly in the area). [[Windsor, Ontario|Windsor]]-[[Detroit, Michigan|Detroit]] was very adversely affected{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} by this spectrum allocation limitation.
*[[The Home Depot]] and [[Lowes]] in the American [[retail]] [[home improvement]] market.
*[[Kodak]] and [[Fujifilm]] in [[motion picture]] [[film stock]] and color [[135 film]] markets
*[[Kesko|K-Kauppa]] and [[S-Group]] in the [[Finland|Finnish]] supermarket market (jointly they control 75% of supermarket market)
*[[Foodstuffs]] and [[Progressive Enterprises]] in the [[New Zealand]] supermarket market (jointly they control 90% of supermarket market)
*[[Woolworths Limited|Woolworths]] and [[Coles Supermarkets|Coles]] in the [[Australia]]n supermarket market (share 79% of the supermarket market)&lt;ref&gt;http://www.weeklytimesnow.com.au/article/2008/11/03/20101_latest-news.html Weeklytimesnow.com.au - Coles, Woolworths still dominate&lt;/ref&gt;
*[[Nvidia]] and the [[ATI]] subsidiary of [[Advanced Micro Devices]] in the mainstream [[graphics card]] market.
*[[LexisNexis]] and [[Westlaw]] in legal research; the two companies together have been jokingly referred to as [[Wexis]]
*[[PetroChina]] and [[Sinopec]] in Chinese oil production.
*[[Pakistan State Oil (PSO)]] and [[Shell Pakistan]] in white oil products in Pakistan (share almost 90% of the white oil market in the country)
*[[RAI|Rai]] and [[Mediaset]] in the Italian television market.
*[[Dish Network]] and [[DirecTV]] in the U.S. satellite provider market.
*[[Televisa]] and [[Azteca (television)|Azteca]] in the Mexican multimedia market. (jointly they control 95% of the multimedia market)
*[[Handango]] and [[Motricity]] in mobile content retailing market.
*[[Migros]] and [[Coop]] in Swiss retail food market.
*[[FedEx]] and [[United Parcel Service|UPS]] in the United States express small package delivery industry.
*[[MillerCoors]] and [[Anheuser-Busch]] in the United States Domestic beer market.
*[[Canon (company)|Canon]] and [[Nikon]] in high end imaging optics, film and digital cameras (especially in DSLRs)
*[[Kleenex]] and [[Puffs]] in facial tissues.
*[[RTM]] and [[Media Prima]] in Malaysia's free-to-air TV station market.
*[[Starhub]] and [[Singtel]] in Singapore's cable television market.
*[[SMRT Corporation]] and [[SBS Transit]] in Singapore's Transport
*[[Verizon]] and [[AT&amp;T]] in the U.S. telecommunications market.
*[[GeoEye]] and [[DigitalGlobe]] in the U.S. satellite imaging market.
*[[Mitre 10| Mitre 10 MEGA]] and [[Bunnings Warehouse]] in the Australian and New Zealand retail/trade timber and hardware market (Share 85% of the timber and hardware market).&lt;ref&gt;http://www.insideretailing.com.au/Default.aspx?tabid=53&amp;articleType=ArticleView&amp;articleId=3709 Insideretailing.com.au Some positive signs in the Coles businesses under Wesfarmers&lt;/ref&gt;
*[[Leitner-Poma]] and [[Doppelmayr CTEC]] in the [[chairlift]] industry.

==Media==
In Finland, the state-owned broadcasting company [[Yleisradio]] and the private broadcaster [[MTV3|Mainos-TV]] had a legal duopoly (in the economists' sense of the word) from the 1950s to 1993. No other broadcasters were allowed. Mainos-TV operated by leasing air time from Yleisradio, broadcasting in reserved blocks between Yleisradio's own programming on its two channels. This was a unique phenomenon in the world. Between 1986 and 1992 there was an independent third channel but it was jointly owned by Yle and MTV; only in 1993 did MTV get its own channel.
Safaricom mobile service provider and Zain in Kenya are perfect examples of Duopoly market in African telecommunication industry.

==Broadcasting==
{{Main|Duopoly (broadcasting)}}
[[Duopoly (broadcasting)|Duopoly]] is also used in the [[United States]] broadcast television and radio industry to refer to a single company owning two outlets in the same city.

This usage is technically incompatible with the normal definition of the word and leads to confusion, inasmuch as there are generally more than two owners of broadcast television stations in markets with broadcast duopolies. In [[Canada]], this definition is therefore more commonly called a &quot;[[twinstick]]&quot;.

==Board Games==
The board game [[Monopoly Junior]] is sometimes referred to as &quot;Duopoly&quot;.{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}}

