In the [[United States]], the phrase '''Kennedy family''' commonly refers to the family descending from the marriage of the [[Irish American|Irish-Americans]] [[Joseph P. Kennedy, Sr.]] and [[Rose Fitzgerald Kennedy|Rose Elizabeth Fitzgerald]] that was prominent in [[Politics of the United States|American politics]] and government. Their political involvement has revolved around the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]. [[Harvard University]] educations have been common among them, and they have contributed heavily to that university's [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]]. The wealth, glamour &lt;!--&quot;glamour&quot; is probably the more-common u.s. spelling (as in &quot;Glamour&quot; magazine)--&gt; and photogenic quality of the family members, as well as their extensive and continuing commitment to public service, has elevated them to [[Cultural icon|iconic]] status over the past half-century and has led to their reputation as &quot;America's Royal Family.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G1-86872042.html&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/08/21/sorensen.kennedy.family/index.html | work=CNN | title=Commentary: Kennedy family's remarkable story - CNN.com | accessdate=May 7, 2010 | date=August 26, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;http://www.capecodonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/section?category=SPECIAL18&lt;/ref&gt;

Following the [[United States presidential election, 1960|1960 election]] of [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[John F. Kennedy]], he and his two younger brothers, [[Robert F. Kennedy]] and [[Ted Kennedy|Edward M. Kennedy]], soon all held prominent positions in the federal government, and received intensive publicity, often emphasizing their youth (relative to comparably influential politicians), allure, education and collective future in politics. From 1947, when John F. Kennedy was first elected to Congress, to 2011, when [[Patrick J. Kennedy]] departed Congress, there was a 64-year run of a Kennedy family member holding an elective office in Washington.&lt;ref name=&quot;bg021310&quot;&gt;{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/rhode_island/articles/2010/02/13/pondering_a_congress_without_kennedys/ |title=Pondering a Congress without Kennedys |author=Levenson, Michael |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=February 13, 2010 |accessdate=March 28, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; This spans more than a quarter of the nation's existence.&lt;ref name=&quot;bg021310&quot;/&gt;

The family has suffered numerous tragedies known as &quot;[[Kennedy tragedies|the Kennedy curse]]&quot;, including the assassination of brothers [[John F. Kennedy assassination|John]] and [[Robert F. Kennedy assassination|Robert]], the controversial [[Chappaquiddick incident]], and four airplane crashes ([[Joseph P. Kennedy, Jr.|Joe, Jr.]], [[Kathleen Cavendish, Marchioness of Hartington|Kathleen]], Ted and [[John F. Kennedy, Jr.|John, Jr.]], all but Ted were fatal).

==Family tree==
{{See|List of descendants of Joseph P. and Rose Fitzgerald Kennedy|Kennedy family political line}}
----
{{Kennedy family tree}}&lt;!--August 31, 2009 - this editor updated family tree template to include 2nd wife of Ted; however, did not yet update to include his 2 stepchildren - see hidden note in template article--&gt; 
----
===First generation===	
The family [[patriarch]] was [[P. J. Kennedy|Patrick J. Kennedy]] (1858–1929), a [[Immigrant generations#First generation immigrant|first-generation]] American who married [[Mary Augusta Hickey Kennedy|Mary Augusta Hickey]] (1857–1923). He was a politician involved in the local Democratic Party.

===Second generation===
In 1914, their son, [[Joseph P. Kennedy, Sr.]] (1888–1969) married [[Rose Fitzgerald Kennedy|Rose Fitzgerald]] (1890–1995), the daughter of [[List of mayors of Boston|Boston (Massachusetts) Mayor]] [[John F. Fitzgerald]]. Joseph served as the first chairman of the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] and as the [[United States Ambassador to the United Kingdom|U.S. Ambassador to the United Kingdom]] in the years leading up to [[World War II]].

===Third generation===
Together Joseph and Rose Kennedy had nine children:
[[File:The Kennedy Family in Hyannis Port, 1948.jpg|thumb|right|[[Joseph P. Kennedy Sr|Joseph Sr.]] and [[Rose Fitzgerald Kennedy|Rose Kennedy]] with six of their nine children; [[John F. Kennedy]], [[Jean Kennedy]], [[Patricia Kennedy]], [[Robert F. Kennedy]], [[Eunice Kennedy]] and [[Edward M. Kennedy]] at the [[Kennedy Compound]] in Hyannis Port, Massachusetts, 1948. Other children not pictured include [[Joseph P. Kennedy, Jr.]], [[Rosemary Kennedy]], and [[Kathleen Cavendish, Marchioness of Hartington|Kathleen Kennedy]].]]
[[Image:Kennedy bros.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Irish Catholic]] political dynasty, [[John F. Kennedy|John]], [[Robert Kennedy|Robert]], and [[Ted Kennedy|Edward Kennedy]], July 1960.]] 

* [[Joseph P. Kennedy, Jr.|Joseph Patrick Kennedy, Jr.]] (1915–1944)
** Died during World War II when taking part in [[Operation Aphrodite]] as a pilot of a modified [[B-24 Liberator]] drone bomber which accidentally exploded and crashed over [[River Blyth, Suffolk|Blyth Estuary]] near [[Suffolk]], [[England]]. For this act, he was [[posthumous recognition|posthumously]] awarded the [[Navy Cross]]. His body was never recovered.
* [[John F. Kennedy|John Fitzgerald Kennedy]] (1917–1963)
** Known to his family as &quot;Jack&quot; and sometimes referred to as &quot;JFK&quot;, he was a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] (1947–1953), a U.S. Senator (1953–1960) and the 35th U.S. President (1961–1963). In 1953, he married [[Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis|Jacqueline Lee Bouvier]] (1929–1994) and they had four children, one of whom was stillborn, one died soon after birth, and two survived to adulthood. [[John F. Kennedy assassination|He was assassinated on November 22, 1963 while riding in a presidential motorcade]] in [[Dallas]], [[Texas]].
* [[Rosemary Kennedy|Rose Marie Kennedy]] (1918–2005)
** Known as &quot;Rosemary&quot; or &quot;Rosie&quot;, she was rendered incapable of intelligible speech or caring for herself by a prefrontal lobotomy at age 23— a popular [[neurosurgery|neurosurgical]] technique of the time and requested by her father — that was intended to cure her increasing [[mood swing]]s and make her more manageable. The operation instead reduced her to an infantile state. From 1949, she lived in a [[Care of residents|residential-care facility]] in [[Jefferson, Wisconsin|Jefferson]], [[Wisconsin]], until her death.
* [[Kathleen Cavendish, Marchioness of Hartington|Kathleen Agnes Kennedy]] (1920–1948)
** Known as &quot;Kick&quot;, in 1944 she married a [[Protestantism|Protestant]], [[William Cavendish, Marquess of Hartington|William John Robert Cavendish, Marquess of Hartington]] (1917–1944) — the son and heir to the [[Duke of Devonshire]] — over her mother's strenuous religious objections. After being widowed when her husband was [[killed in action]] during World War II, she was killed in an airplane crash in [[France]] along with her lover, [[Peter Wentworth-Fitzwilliam, 8th Earl Fitzwilliam]] (1910–1948).
* [[Eunice Kennedy Shriver|Eunice Mary Kennedy]] (1921–2009)
** She was a co-founder of the [[Special Olympics]] in 1968, an organization she began in honor of her sister Rosemary. In 1953, she married [[Sargent Shriver|Robert Sargent Shriver, Jr.]] (1915–2011), who was later the [[United States Ambassador to France|U.S. Ambassador to France]] in the late 1960s-early 1970s and a [[United States presidential election, 1972|1972 vice-presidential candidate]]; they had five children.
* [[Patricia Kennedy Lawford|Patricia Kennedy]] (1924–2006)
** Married actor [[Peter Lawford]] (1923–1984) in 1954. They had four children and divorced in 1966.
* [[Robert F. Kennedy|Robert Francis Kennedy]] (1925–1968)
** Known as &quot;Bob&quot; or &quot;Bobby&quot; and sometimes referred to as &quot;RFK&quot;, he was [[Attorney General of the United States|U.S. Attorney General]] (1961–1964) in his brother John's administration and later served as the junior U.S. Senator from [[New York]] (1965-his death). In 1950, he married [[Ethel Skakel Kennedy|Ethel Skakel]] (b. 1928) and they had 11 children. He was assassinated in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] during his [[United States presidential election, 1968|1968 campaign for U.S. president]].
* [[Jean Ann Kennedy|Jean Kennedy Smith]] (b. 1928)
** In 1956, she married [[Stephen Edward Smith]] (1927–1990) and they had two sons and adopted two daughters. She later served as the [[United States Ambassador to Ireland|U.S. Ambassador to Ireland]] (1993–1998).
* [[Ted Kennedy|Edward Moore Kennedy]] (1932–2009)
** Known as &quot;Teddy&quot; or &quot;Ted&quot;, he served as a U.S. Senator from Massachusetts (1962–2009). In 1958, he married [[Joan Bennett Kennedy|Virginia Joan Bennett]] (b. 1936) and they had three children; they divorced in 1981. In 1992, he married [[Victoria Reggie Kennedy|Victoria Anne Reggie]] (b. 1954) and had two stepchildren from this marriage. On May 20, 2008, it was announced that he had a malignant brain tumor. In the next year, brain cancer severely limited his U.S. Senate appearances. He died on August 25, 2009.

====Third-generation in-laws====
*[[Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis|Jacqueline Lee Bouvier]] (1929–1994), wife of John
*[[Sargent Shriver|Robert Sargent Shriver, Jr.]] (1915–2011), husband of Eunice
*[[Peter Lawford]] (1923–1984), former husband of Patricia
*[[Ethel Skakel Kennedy|Ethel Skakel]] (b. 1928), wife of Robert
*[[Stephen Edward Smith|Stephen Edward Smith, Sr]] (1927–1990), husband of Jean
*[[Joan Bennett Kennedy|Virginia Joan Bennett]] (b. 1936), first wife of Edward
*[[Victoria Reggie Kennedy|Victoria Anne Reggie]] (b. 1954), second wife of Edward

===Fourth generation===

* John Fitzgerald Kennedy and Jacqueline Lee Bouvier had four children:
*# Arabella Kennedy (1956) — [[stillbirth|stillborn]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Spoto&quot;&gt;{{cite book |title=Jacqueline Bouvier Kennedy Onassis: A Life |last=Spoto |first=Donald |year=2000 |publisher=Macmillan |isbn=0312977077 |page=136}}&lt;/ref&gt;
*# [[Caroline Kennedy|Caroline Bouvier Kennedy]] (b. 1957) — a lawyer, a co-founder of the [[Profile in Courage Award]]&lt;!--&quot;Profile&quot; is singular--&gt;, the president of the [[John F. Kennedy Library|John F. Kennedy Library Foundation]] and the chairwoman of the [[American Ballet Theatre]]. Married [[Edwin Schlossberg]]; has three children.
*# [[John F. Kennedy, Jr.|John Fitzgerald Kennedy, Jr.]] (1960–1999) — [[John F. Kennedy, Jr. plane crash|died in an plane crash]] on July 16, 1999.
*# [[Patrick Bouvier Kennedy]] (1963) — died from [[infant respiratory distress syndrome|infant respiratory-distress syndrome]] two days after his birth.

* Rose Marie &quot;Rosemary&quot; Kennedy neither married nor had children.

* Kathleen Agnes Kennedy and William John Robert Cavendish, Marquess of Hartington had no children.

* Eunice Mary Kennedy and Robert Sargent Shriver, Jr. had five children:
*# [[Bobby Shriver|Robert Sargent Shriver III]] (b. 1954) — an attorney and the president of RSS Inc., a [[Beverly Hills, California|Beverly Hills]], [[California]], music, film and philanthropic company; a [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica]], California, city councilman And Mayor. Married Malissa Ferzuzzi; has two daughters.
*# [[Maria Shriver|Maria Owings Shriver]] (b. 1955) — a former [[News presenter|television news anchor]]; former [[First Lady]] of California as wife of [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Governor of California|California Governor]] [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] (b. 1947); has four children.
*# [[Timothy Shriver|Timothy Perry Shriver]] (b. 1959) — former [[New Haven, Connecticut]] educator, since 1997 the [[chairman]] of the [[Special Olympics]]. Married Linda S. Potter; has five children.
*# [[Mark Shriver|Mark Kennedy Shriver]] (b. 1964) — a former [[Delegate]] in the [[Maryland General Assembly]] currently Vice President and Managing Director of US Programs for the charity Save the Children. Married Jeannie Ripp; has three children.
*# [[Anthony Shriver|Anthony Paul Kennedy Shriver]] (b. 1965) — an activist for [[mental retardation]] and founded [[Best Buddies International]]. Married Alina Mojica; has five children.

* Patricia Kennedy and Peter Lawford had four children, notably:
*# [[Christopher Lawford|Christopher Kennedy Lawford]] (b. 1955) — a professional actor. Divorced from Jeannie Olsson; has three children.
*# [[Robin Elizabeth Lawford]] (b. 1961) — an environmentalist and [[marine biologist]].

* Robert Francis Kennedy and Ethel Skakel had 11 children:
*# [[Kathleen Kennedy Townsend|Kathleen Hartington Kennedy]] (b. 1951) — former [[Lt. Governor of Maryland]], a candidate for [[Governor of Maryland]]. Married David Lee Townsend; has four daughters.
*# [[Joseph Patrick Kennedy II]] (b. 1952) — former [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Massachusetts]]. Runs the non-profit Citizens Energy Corp. in [[Boston]]. Divorced from Sheila Rauch; two sons. Married to Anne Elizabeth (&quot;Beth&quot;) Kelly; no children.
*# [[Robert F. Kennedy, Jr.|Robert Francis Kennedy, Jr.]] (b. 1954) — an environmentalist and political commentator, attorney and law professor at [[Pace University School of Law]]; best known for his many successful [[lawsuit|litigation]]s to prevent water pollution, primarily in the [[New York]] area. Divorced from Emily Ruth Black; two children. Married Mary Richardson; four children.
*# [[David Kennedy|David Anthony Kennedy]] (1955–1984) — died of a [[drug overdose]] in a [[Palm Beach, Florida]] hotel room on April 25, 1984. He was neither married nor had children.
*# [[Courtney Kennedy Hill|Mary Courtney Kennedy]] (b. 1956) — divorced from Jeffrey Robert Ruhe. Separated from [[Guildford Four and Maguire Seven#Guildford Four|Paul Michael Hill]]; has one daughter.
*# [[Michael LeMoyne Kennedy]] (1958–1997) — died in an [[Aspen, Colorado]] [[skiing]] accident on December 31, 1997. Separated from Victoria Gifford, a daughter of [[Frank Gifford]]; had three children.
*# [[Kerry Kennedy|Mary Kerry Kennedy]] (b. 1959) — human rights activist with the Robert F. Kennedy Center for Justice and Human Rights. Divorced from [[Andrew Cuomo]]; has three daughters.
*# [[Christopher G. Kennedy|Christopher George Kennedy]] (b. 1963) — the president of [[Merchandise Mart]] commercial properties based in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]. Married Sheila Sinclair Berner; has four children.
*# [[Max Kennedy|Matthew Maxwell Taylor Kennedy]] (b. 1965) — an author and lawyer. Married Victoria Anne Stauss, has three children.
*# [[Douglas Harriman Kennedy]] (b. 1967) — a journalist, news reporter for FOX News. Married Mary Elizabeth Stark; has three daughters.
*# [[Rory Kennedy|Rory Elizabeth Katherine Kennedy]] (b. 1968) — an award-winning [[Documentary film|documentary]] [[filmmaker]] and [[Film producer|producer]]. Married Mark Bailey; has three children.

*Jean Ann Kennedy and Stephen Edward Smith, Sr. had four children:
*# Stephen Edward Smith, Jr. (b. 1957) — attorney, crisis counselor and real estate developer.
*# [[William Kennedy Smith]] (b. 1960) — a [[physician]] and activist against [[land mine]]s. He has neither married nor had children. [[Acquitted]] in 1991 of [[rape]] charges.
*# Amanda Mary Smith (b. 1967; adopted). Married attorney (Harmon) Carter Hood; has two children.
*# Kym Maria Smith (b. 1972; adopted) — photographer. Divorced from Alfie Tucker; married to John Morgan.

*Edward &quot;Ted&quot; Moore Kennedy (1932–2009) and Virginia Joan Bennett had three children:
*# [[Kara Kennedy Allen|Kara Anne Kennedy]] (b. 1960) — board member, television producer. Married Michael Allen; has two children.
*# [[Edward Kennedy, Jr.|Edward Moore &quot;Ted&quot; Kennedy, Jr.]] (b. 1961) — a co-founder and the president of the [[Marwood Group]], a Wall Street investment firm. Married Katharine (&quot;Kiki&quot;) Anne Gershman; has two children.
*# [[Patrick Joseph Kennedy|Patrick Joseph Kennedy II]] (b. 1967) — former [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Rhode Island]]. He has neither married nor had children.

:Edward Moore &quot;Ted&quot; Kennedy also had two stepchildren from his marriage to Victoria Anne Reggie — Curran Raclin (b. 1982) and Caroline Raclin (b. 1985).

