    <title>Logical disjunction</title>
    <id>7962</id>
    <revision>
      <id>427110546</id>
      <timestamp>2011-05-02T18:52:33Z</timestamp>
      <contributor>
        <ip>99.88.42.227</ip>
      </contributor>
      <text xml:space="preserve">{{redirect|Disjunction|separation of chromosomes|Meiosis|disjunctions in distribution|Disjunct distribution}}
[[File:Venn0111.svg|220px|thumb|[[Venn diagram]] of&lt;br&gt;&lt;math&gt;~A \or B&lt;/math&gt;]]
[[File:Venn 0111 1111.svg|220px|thumb|Venn diagram of&lt;br&gt;&lt;math&gt;~A \or B \or C&lt;/math&gt;]]

In [[logic]] and [[mathematics]], a two-place [[logical operator]] '''or''', is a '''logical disjunction''', also known as '''inclusive disjunction''' or '''alternation''', that results in true whenever ''one or more'' of its operands are true. E.g. in this context, &quot;''A'' or ''B''&quot; is true [[if]] ''A'' is true, or if ''B'' is true, or if both ''A'' and ''B'' are true. In [[grammar]], '''or''' is a [[Grammatical conjunction|coordinating conjunction]]. In ordinary language &quot;or&quot; sometimes has the meaning of [[exclusive disjunction]].

== Notation ==

'''Or''' is usually expressed with the prefix operator '''A''', or with an infix operator. In mathematics and logic, the infix operator is usually '''∨'''; in electronics, '''+'''; and in programming languages, '''|''' or '''or'''.  Some programming languages have a related [[control structure]], the [[short-circuit evaluation|short-circuit or]], written '''||''', '''or else''', etc.

== Definition ==

'''Logical disjunction''' is an [[logical operation|operation]] on two [[logical value]]s, typically the values of two [[proposition]]s, that produces a value of ''false'' if and only if both of its operands are false. More generally a disjunction is a logical formula that can have one or more [[literal (mathematical logic)|literal]]s separated only by ORs. A single literal is often considered to be a degenerate disjunction.

===Truth table===
[[File:Multigrade operator; OR; 4; argument variation; truth table.svg|thumb|Disjunctions of the arguments on the left&lt;br&gt;The [[truth value|false]] [[bit]]&lt;nowiki&gt;s&lt;/nowiki&gt; form a [[Sierpinski triangle]]]]

The [[truth table]] of &lt;math&gt;~A \or B&lt;/math&gt;:

{| class=&quot;wikitable&quot; style=&quot;margin: 0 0 1em 1em&quot;
|- bgcolor=&quot;#ddeeff&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;
|colspan=2|'''INPUT''' || '''OUTPUT'''
|- bgcolor=&quot;#ddeeff&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;
| A || B || A OR B
|- bgcolor=&quot;#ddffdd&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;
|0 || 0 || 0
|- bgcolor=&quot;#ddffdd&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;
|0 || 1 || 1
|- bgcolor=&quot;#ddffdd&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;
|1 || 0 || 1
|- bgcolor=&quot;#ddffdd&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;
|1 || 1 || 1
|}



